408→                           Dickman <a href="#cite-Di30-928" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Di30','928'); return false;">[Di30]</a> showed the density of smooth $n$, with largest prime factor $&lt;n^\alpha$, is $\rho(1/\alpha)$ where $\rho$ is the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dickman_function" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer ugc" target="_blank">Dickman function</a>.<br><br>Erdős also asked whether infinitely many such $n$ even exist, but Meza has observed that this follows immediately from Schinzel's result <a href="#cite-Sc67b-928" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Sc67b','928'); return false;">[Sc67b]</a> that for infinitely many $n$ the largest prime factor of $n(n+1)$ is at most $n^{O(1/\log\log n)}$.<br><br>Erdős asked whether the events $P(n)&lt;n^\alpha$ and $P(n+1)&lt;(n+1)^\beta$ are independent, in the sense that the density of $n$ satisfying both conditions is equal to $\rho(1/\alpha)\rho(1/\beta)$. <br><br>Teräväinen <a href="#cite-Te18-928" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Te18','928'); return false;">[Te18]</a> has proved the logarithmic density exists and is equal to $\rho(1/\alpha)\rho(1/\beta)$. <br><br>Wang <a href="#cite-Wa21-928" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Wa21','928'); return false;">[Wa21]</a> has proved the density is $\rho(1/\alpha)\rho(1/\beta)$  assuming the Elliott-Halberstam conjecture for friable integers.<br><br>See also <a href="/370" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer ugc" target="_blank">[370]</a>.
